To convert between screen coordinates and virtual coordinates, you can use the SDL_RenderSetLogicalSize and SDL_RenderSetViewport functions in SDL2.

Here's an example of how you can do this:

1. Set up the logical size using SDL_RenderSetLogicalSize. This specifies the size of the virtual coordinate system you want to use.

```cpp
int logicalWidth = 800;
int logicalHeight = 600;

SDL_RenderSetLogicalSize(renderer, logicalWidth, logicalHeight);
```

2. Calculate the scaling factors for X and Y axes based on the actual screen size and the logical size.

```cpp
int screenWidth, screenHeight;
SDL_GetRendererOutputSize(renderer, &screenWidth, &screenHeight);

float scaleX = (float)screenWidth / logicalWidth;
float scaleY = (float)screenHeight / logicalHeight;
```

3. Set up the viewport using SDL_RenderSetViewport. This defines the portion of the screen where the virtual coordinate system is rendered.

```cpp
SDL_Rect viewport;
viewport.x = 0;
viewport.y = 0;
viewport.w = screenWidth;
viewport.h = screenHeight;

SDL_RenderSetViewport(renderer, &viewport);
```

4. Convert coordinates between the virtual coordinate system and screen coordinate system.
   - To convert virtual coordinates to screen coordinates, multiply the coordinates by the scaling factors:

```cpp
int virtualX = 100;
int virtualY = 200;

int screenX = virtualX * scaleX;
int screenY = virtualY * scaleY;
```

- To convert screen coordinates to virtual coordinates, divide the coordinates by the scaling factors:

```cpp
int screenX = 400;
int screenY = 300;

int virtualX = screenX / scaleX;
int virtualY = screenY / scaleY;
```

Remember to include the necessary SDL headers and initialize the SDL renderer before using these functions.

