To determine if a value is a whole number in C++ with SDL2, you can use the std::floor function from the <cmath> library and compare the value before and after applying the floor function. If the values are equal, it means the value was already a whole number. Otherwise, it has decimal places.

Here's an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <cmath>

int main() {
    double value = 3.14;

    // Check if value is a whole number
    if (std::floor(value) == value) {
        std::cout << "Value is a whole number." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Value is not a whole number." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, if the variable `value` has the value `3.14`, the output will be "Value is not a whole number."

If you want to use an SDL2 specific function to check if a value is a whole number, you can use the SDL_floor function from the <SDL2/SDL_stdinc.h> header. It behaves similarly to the std::floor function.

Here's an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <SDL2/SDL_stdinc.h>

int main() {
    double value = 5.0;

    // Check if value is a whole number
    if (SDL_floor(value) == value) {
        std::cout << "Value is a whole number." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Value is not a whole number." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, if the variable `value` has the value `5.0`, the output will be "Value is a whole number."

Yes, it is possible to scale an SDL viewport by the same amount that SDL scales the screen with SDL_SetLogicalSize. 

To achieve this, you can calculate the scaling factors for the viewport based on the logical size and the actual screen size. Then, use these scaling factors to adjust the viewport coordinates.

Here's an example of how you can do this:

```cpp
int logicalWidth = 800;
int logicalHeight = 600;

int screenWidth, screenHeight;
SDL_GetRendererOutputSize(renderer, &screenWidth, &screenHeight);

float scaleX = (float)screenWidth / logicalWidth;
float scaleY = (float)screenHeight / logicalHeight;

SDL_Rect viewport;
viewport.x = 0;
viewport.y = 0;
viewport.w = logicalWidth;
viewport.h = logicalHeight;

SDL_RenderSetViewport(renderer, &viewport);
```

Now, if you draw something on the logical coordinate system using SDL_RenderDrawRect, for example, it will be scaled to fit within the specified logical size on the screen.

```cpp
int logicalRectX = 100;
int logicalRectY = 100;
int logicalRectW = 200;
int logicalRectH = 150;

int screenRectX = logicalRectX * scaleX;
int screenRectY = logicalRectY * scaleY;
int screenRectW = logicalRectW * scaleX;
int screenRectH = logicalRectH * scaleY;

SDL_Rect screenRect;
screenRect.x = screenRectX;
screenRect.y = screenRectY;
screenRect.w = screenRectW;
screenRect.h = screenRectH;

SDL_RenderDrawRect(renderer, &screenRect);
```

This example will draw a rectangle with logical coordinates (100, 100, 200, 150) but scaled to fit within the logical size on the screen.

Remember to include the necessary SDL headers, initialize the SDL renderer, and handle other SDL-related tasks appropriately in your code.

To make SDL_SetLogicalSize scale by a 1:1 ratio, you need to set the logical size of the window to be the same as the actual size of the window. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

1. Create an SDL window with SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE flag:
```cpp
SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Window Example", SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, 800, 600, SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE);
```

2. Get the actual size of the window:
```cpp
int windowWidth, windowHeight;
SDL_GetWindowSize(window, &windowWidth, &windowHeight);
```

3. Set the logical size of the window to match the actual size:
```cpp
SDL_RenderSetLogicalSize(renderer, windowWidth, windowHeight);
```
This ensures that the logical size of the window matches the size of the actual window to achieve a 1:1 ratio scaling.

4. Handle resizing events:
You may also need to handle SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED events to update the logical size of the window if the user resizes the window. For example:
```cpp
SDL_Event event;
while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
    switch (event.type) {
        case SDL_WINDOWEVENT:
            if (event.window.event == SDL_WINDOWEVENT_RESIZED) {
                SDL_GetWindowSize(window, &windowWidth, &windowHeight);
                SDL_RenderSetLogicalSize(renderer, windowWidth, windowHeight);
            }
            break;
        // handle other events
    }
}
```

Remember to include the necessary SDL headers, initialize SDL, create a renderer, and handle rendering and other SDL-related tasks in your code.

Note: By using SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE, the user will be able to resize the window, which will also update the logical size accordingly. If you don't want the window to be resizable, you can set a fixed size through SDL_CreateWindow or remove the SDL_WINDOW_RESIZABLE flag.

To scale the screen in SDL, you can modify the render target's viewport and logical size. Here's an example on how to achieve this:

1. Create an SDL window and renderer:
```cpp
SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO);

SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Scaling Example", SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, 800, 600, 0);
SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, 0);
```

2. Set the logical size to the desired scaled dimensions:
```cpp
int scaledWidth = 640;
int scaledHeight = 480;
SDL_RenderSetLogicalSize(renderer, scaledWidth, scaledHeight);
```

3. Calculate the scaling factors:
```cpp
int windowWidth, windowHeight;
SDL_GetWindowSize(window, &windowWidth, &windowHeight);

float scaleX = (float)windowWidth / scaledWidth;
float scaleY = (float)windowHeight / scaledHeight;
```

4. Set the viewport to maintain aspect ratio and scale the content:
```cpp
SDL_Rect viewport;
if (windowWidth / (float)windowHeight > scaledWidth / (float)scaledHeight) {
    // Calculate viewport dimensions to maintain width
    int scaledViewportHeight = windowWidth * scaledHeight / scaledWidth;
    int scaledViewportY = (windowHeight - scaledViewportHeight) / 2;
    viewport = { 0, scaledViewportY, windowWidth, scaledViewportHeight };
} else {
    // Calculate viewport dimensions to maintain height
    int scaledViewportWidth = windowHeight * scaledWidth / scaledHeight;
    int scaledViewportX = (windowWidth - scaledViewportWidth) / 2;
    viewport = { scaledViewportX, 0, scaledViewportWidth, windowHeight };
}

SDL_RenderSetViewport(renderer, &viewport);
```

This code calculates the viewport dimensions to maintain the original aspect ratio while scaling the content to fit within the window. It centers the viewport and may add letterboxing or pillarboxing when necessary.

5. Render or perform tasks in the scaled window as needed.

6. Cleanup and quit SDL:
```cpp
SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
SDL_Quit();
```

Remember to handle any errors that may occur during initialization, handle user input, and perform proper error checking throughout your code.

By following this approach, you can scale the content of your SDL window based on the desired scaled dimensions while maintaining the aspect ratio and properly adjusting the viewport.

If you want to scale the screen without using SDL_SetLogicalSize, you can achieve it by modifying the viewport and manually scaling your rendering output. Here's an example:

1. Create an SDL window and renderer:
```cpp
SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO);

SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Scaling Example", SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, 800, 600, 0);
SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, 0);
```

2. Calculate the scaling factors:
```cpp
int originalWidth = 800;
int originalHeight = 600;

int scaledWidth = 640;
int scaledHeight = 480;

float scaleX = (float)scaledWidth / originalWidth;
float scaleY = (float)scaledHeight / originalHeight;
```

3. Set the viewport to the scaled dimensions:
```cpp
SDL_Rect viewport;
viewport.x = 0;
viewport.y = 0;
viewport.w = scaledWidth;
viewport.h = scaledHeight;

SDL_RenderSetViewport(renderer, &viewport);
```

4. Scale your rendering output:
```cpp
SDL_RenderSetScale(renderer, scaleX, scaleY);
```

5. Render or perform tasks as needed with your scaled output.

6. Cleanup and quit SDL:
```cpp
SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
SDL_Quit();
```

By using SDL_RenderSetScale, you are manually scaling the rendering output to match your desired scaled dimensions. The scaling factors scaleX and scaleY are used to adjust the size of the viewport and scale the content accordingly.

Remember to handle any errors that may occur during initialization, handle user input, and perform proper error checking throughout your code.

Note that without using SDL_SetLogicalSize, the mouse coordinates and other SDL functions that rely on the logical size may not be scaled automatically. You may need to manually adjust these values to match your scaling if necessary.

To calculate at what scale 640 is greater than 320, you can divide the larger value (640) by the smaller value (320). The result will give you the scale factor.

```cpp
int largerValue = 640;
int smallerValue = 320;

float scaleFactor = (float)largerValue / smallerValue;

std::cout << "Scale Factor: " << scaleFactor << std::endl;
```

In this example, the scaleFactor will be 2.0, indicating that 640 is twice the size of 320.

To change the position of the rendered screen in SDL2 using C++, you can use the SDL_RenderSetViewport function with updated viewport coordinates. Here's an example:

```cpp
// Create an SDL window and renderer
SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Screen Position Example", SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, 800, 600, 0);
SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, 0);

// Set the current viewport
SDL_Rect viewport;
viewport.x = 100;  // New horizontal position
viewport.y = 50;   // New vertical position
viewport.w = 800;  // Width of the viewport
viewport.h = 600;  // Height of the viewport

SDL_RenderSetViewport(renderer, &viewport);

// Render or perform tasks within the updated viewport position
SDL_RenderClear(renderer);
// Additional rendering operations go here
SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
```

In this example, the SDL_RenderSetViewport function is used to update the position of the rendered screen. The SDL_Rect structure is used to define the new viewport, including the x and y coordinates as the new position relative to the window. You can modify these coordinates to change the screen's position as desired.

Remember to include the necessary SDL headers and handle any necessary error checking in your code.

Note that changing the viewport's position does not affect the window's position on the display. If you need to change the window's position on the screen, you will need to use SDL_SetWindowPosition function before or after updating the viewport position.

